export const earlyModernCorePhilosopherArticles:Record<string,ArticleSection[]>={
  descartes:[
    section('overview','A new beginning that still argues with the old world',[
      'Descartes is often introduced as the founder of modern philosophy because he turns inquiry toward the conditions under which a thinking subject can know anything with certainty. That label is useful only if it does not make him appear to have invented himself from nothing. His work belongs to a seventeenth-century world in which Aristotelian scholasticism still organized much university teaching, mathematical physics was rapidly changing the explanation of nature, religious conflict made authority a serious practical problem, and new instruments and methods were altering the meaning of evidence. Descartes tries to give philosophy a foundation strong enough to survive this unsettled landscape.',
      'The famous method of doubt is not a mood of permanent suspicion. It is an artificial test designed to discover whether anything remains secure when inherited beliefs, sensory confidence, and even mathematical judgments are placed under pressure. What remains first is the thinking self as an indubitable point of awareness: if I am doubting, being deceived, affirming, denying, imagining, or willing, then I exist while I am engaged in that activity. From that starting point Descartes attempts to rebuild knowledge of God, mind, body, and the external world. The ambition is enormous, and the cracks in the project became just as influential as its achievements.'
    ],['rationalism','epistemology','metaphysics','philosophy-of-mind'],['descartes','spinoza','leibniz','locke','hume','kant','aristotle','aquinas'],['Discourse on Method','Meditations on First Philosophy','Principles of Philosophy']),
    section('historical-setting','Scholastic inheritance and the new science',[
      'Descartes was educated in a world still shaped by Aristotle as interpreted through medieval and Renaissance scholastic traditions. Substances, forms, qualities, final causes, and hierarchical natural orders provided much of the inherited vocabulary. Scholastic philosophy was not a single crude doctrine, and it included subtle logical, metaphysical, and theological work. Descartes nevertheless thought that many explanations in natural philosophy failed to produce the kind of clarity and control that mathematics displayed. His criticism is partly philosophical and partly methodological: he wants principles that allow nature to be understood through extension, motion, and lawlike relations rather than through obscure qualities.',
      'The scientific setting matters. Galileo, Kepler, mechanics, optics, anatomy, and debates about the structure of the cosmos made older forms of explanation look vulnerable. Descartes participated in this transformation through work in geometry, optics, physiology, and physics. He admired mathematical order because it displays steps that can be reviewed and repeated by the mind. His dream was not merely to add a new theory beside old theories, but to reorganize inquiry so that metaphysics, physics, and practical knowledge could hang together. Even when his particular physics was displaced, the demand for method and clear principles remained powerful.'
    ],['philosophy-of-science','metaphysics','rationalism'],['descartes','aristotle','aquinas'],['Discourse on Method','Principles of Philosophy','The World']),
    section('life-and-caution','Life, publication, and philosophical caution',[
      'Descartes was born in 1596 in La Haye en Touraine in France and was educated by Jesuits at La Fleche. He later studied law, served in military contexts, traveled, and eventually spent much of his mature intellectual life in the Dutch Republic, where relative freedom and active print culture made sustained work possible. His life was not that of a professor teaching a fixed curriculum. He wrote for learned readers across Europe, corresponded widely, and tried to shape a new intellectual movement while avoiding some of the dangers that came with challenging established authorities.',
      'His caution was not imaginary. The condemnation of Galileo in 1633 affected Descartes directly. He withheld or delayed publication of work that presented a mechanistic cosmology partly because he did not want to provoke theological censure. This background helps explain the careful architecture of the Meditations: the work is addressed to learned and theological readers, includes arguments for God and the distinction of mind from body, and tries to show that the new science need not undermine religion. The result is not simple camouflage. Descartes genuinely thinks metaphysics must secure science, but the way he presents that project is shaped by institutional risk.'
    ],['rationalism','philosophy-of-religion','philosophy-of-science'],['descartes'],['Meditations on First Philosophy','Discourse on Method','The World']),
    section('methodical-doubt','Methodical doubt and the search for certainty',[
      'The Meditations begins by withdrawing assent from beliefs that can be doubted. Sensory beliefs are vulnerable because the senses sometimes mislead. Dreaming raises a deeper problem: while dreaming, a person can believe they are awake, so the immediate feeling of being present in the world does not by itself guarantee that the world is as it seems. The evil deceiver hypothesis radicalizes doubt even further by imagining a powerful source of deception capable of making even simple judgments appear certain when they are false. Descartes is not claiming that such a deceiver exists. He is constructing a test severe enough to expose what cannot be doubted even under extreme conditions.',
      'The point of the method is often misunderstood. Descartes is not recommending that ordinary life be lived in paralysis, and he is not treating skepticism as the final truth. He wants to defeat skepticism by passing through it in an ordered way. The method also distinguishes levels of belief. Some beliefs are merely inherited, some are probable, some are practically necessary, and some may be known with complete clarity. By suspending the lower levels for philosophical purposes, Descartes hopes to find a foundation that is not borrowed from authority or habit. The cost is that the path back from the isolated thinking subject to a shared world becomes difficult.'
    ],['epistemology','rationalism'],['descartes','hume','kant'],['Meditations on First Philosophy']),
    section('cogito','The cogito and the thinking self',[
      'The cogito is the first secure result of the doubt. However radically I am deceived, I cannot be deceived about my existence while I am thinking. The insight is sometimes compressed into a slogan, but in the Meditations it functions as an act of immediate recognition rather than as a formal syllogism. If I doubt, I think; if I think, I am. The certainty is not that I know everything about myself, or that I am a soul in the full theological sense. The certainty is that the act of thinking reveals the existence of the thinker at the moment of thinking.',
      'This discovery changes the starting point of philosophy. The self first known is not a biological organism, a social role, or an Aristotelian substance identified through a natural kind. It is a res cogitans, a thinking thing, whose modes include doubting, understanding, affirming, denying, willing, refusing, imagining, and sensing insofar as sensing is an episode of consciousness. Descartes still needs to show that bodies exist and that the sensory world is trustworthy under the right conditions. The priority of thought becomes a source of both strength and trouble: it gives certainty, but it can also seem to trap philosophy inside consciousness.'
    ],['epistemology','philosophy-of-mind','metaphysics'],['descartes','locke','hume','kant'],['Meditations on First Philosophy']),
    section('clear-distinct-god','Clear and distinct perception, God, and the Cartesian circle',[
      'Descartes argues that whatever he perceives clearly and distinctly is true. Clear perception is present and manifest to an attentive mind; distinct perception is sharply separated from other ideas. Mathematics provides a model of such perception, but the Meditations also tries to secure the rule metaphysically through the existence and non-deceptive nature of God. If God is perfect and not a deceiver, then the faculties God gives us are trustworthy when used properly. Error arises not because God designed reason badly, but because the will extends beyond what the intellect clearly grasps.',
      'The proof of God and the validation of clear and distinct perception produce one of the most famous interpretive problems in Descartes: the so-called Cartesian circle. Does Descartes rely on clear and distinct perception to prove God, while relying on God to guarantee clear and distinct perception? Defenders distinguish between the immediate certainty of a present clear perception and the general assurance that remembered clear perceptions remain trustworthy. Critics argue that the system still depends on a circular guarantee. The dispute matters because it shows the pressure created by Descartes\' foundational ambition. He wants reason to certify itself without leaving any unexamined authority behind.'
    ],['epistemology','metaphysics','philosophy-of-religion','rationalism'],['descartes','spinoza','leibniz'],['Meditations on First Philosophy']),
    section('mind-body-dualism','Mind, body, and the problem of interaction',[
      'Descartes distinguishes mind and body through their principal attributes. Mind is thinking; body is extension. A body is spatial, divisible, and subject to mechanical explanation. A mind is not extended in space and is known through acts of consciousness. This distinction supports Descartes\' claim that the mind can be clearly and distinctly understood apart from the body, and therefore that mind and body are really distinct substances. It also serves theological and moral aims by protecting the soul from reduction to matter.',
      'The problem appears immediately: if mind and body are really distinct, how do they interact? Human life seems full of interaction. Bodily injury produces pain; intention moves limbs; emotion involves both thought and physiology. Descartes discussed the pineal gland as a point of coordination, but that suggestion did not solve the deeper metaphysical problem of how an unextended thinking substance could causally affect extended matter. Later philosophers respond in sharply different ways. Spinoza rejects the dualism of two substances. Leibniz develops pre-established harmony. Occasionalists appeal to divine coordination. Locke and Hume shift attention toward the limits of what experience can show.'
    ],['philosophy-of-mind','metaphysics','rationalism'],['descartes','spinoza','leibniz','locke','hume'],['Meditations on First Philosophy','Passions of the Soul']),
    section('ideas-representation','Ideas, representation, and the external world',[
      'Descartes\' theory of ideas is central to his epistemology. Ideas are modes of thought that represent things. Some seem adventitious, arriving through the senses; some are invented by the imagination; some are innate in the sense that the mind has a capacity to produce or recognize them from its own nature. The idea of God is especially important because Descartes argues that a finite imperfect thinker could not be the adequate cause of the idea of an infinite perfect being. Whether that argument succeeds or not, it shows how Descartes links representation, causation, and metaphysical hierarchy.',
      'The external world reenters the system only after God has been established as no deceiver. Descartes does not say that every sensory appearance is accurate. A square tower can look round from a distance, and pain does not reveal a tiny picture of bodily damage. Sense perception is primarily useful for the preservation of embodied life, while intellect grasps the mathematical nature of body more clearly. This creates a new picture of nature: color, taste, smell, heat, and other sensible qualities become less fundamental than size, shape, motion, and number. The modern distinction between primary and secondary qualities is not exactly Descartes\' alone, but his mechanistic philosophy helped make it unavoidable.'
    ],['epistemology','metaphysics','philosophy-of-science'],['descartes','locke'],['Meditations on First Philosophy','Principles of Philosophy','Optics']),
    section('science-and-mechanism','Mechanism, mathematics, and the living body',[
      'Descartes\' natural philosophy treats the material world as an extended system governed by motion and mechanical laws. He rejects explanations that appeal to substantial forms and many scholastic qualities, arguing instead that physical events should be explained through the arrangement and movement of matter. His physics included vortices, laws of motion, accounts of light, and a mechanistic treatment of bodily functions. Many details did not survive later science, especially after Newton, but the general aspiration to explain nature mathematically and mechanically became a major feature of early modern thought.',
      'His account of animals and the human body is especially revealing. Descartes often describes nonhuman animals as machines lacking rational souls, a view that remains controversial and easily caricatured. He did not deny that animals have complex behavior, but he explained that behavior mechanistically rather than through thought in the strict sense. Human beings, by contrast, combine a machine-like body with a thinking mind. This picture encourages powerful physiological investigation, but it also raises ethical and conceptual questions about animal experience, embodiment, and whether mental life can be separated as cleanly from bodily organization as Descartes hoped.'
    ],['philosophy-of-science','philosophy-of-mind','metaphysics'],['descartes','aristotle'],['Discourse on Method','Principles of Philosophy','Treatise on Man']),
    section('ethics-passions','Ethics, the passions, and provisional morality',[
      'Descartes is not only an epistemologist and metaphysician. In the Discourse on Method he offers a provisional morality for living while inquiry is incomplete. Since action cannot wait for perfect knowledge, one should obey the laws and customs of one\'s country, remain firm once a reasonable course is chosen, seek to master oneself rather than fortune, and cultivate reason. These maxims are sometimes treated as secondary, but they show Descartes\' awareness that doubt is a philosophical exercise, not a permanent practical stance.',
      'The Passions of the Soul develops a more systematic moral psychology. Passions are perceptions or feelings tied to the union of mind and body. They are not simply irrational disturbances to be crushed. They orient the soul toward what appears beneficial or harmful, and they can be guided by judgment and habit. Generosity, for Descartes, becomes a key virtue because it joins awareness of free will with resolution to use that freedom well. This side of Descartes complicates the stereotype of a pure disembodied rationalist. He knows that human beings are embodied agents whose emotions must be understood, trained, and integrated.'
    ],['ethics','philosophy-of-mind','rationalism'],['descartes'],['Discourse on Method','Passions of the Soul']),
    section('influence-and-reactions','Influence, objections, and later transformations',[
      'Descartes invited objections to the Meditations, and the published work includes replies to major critics. This exchange was part of the philosophy itself. Critics pressed him on the proofs of God, the nature of ideas, the criterion of clarity and distinctness, the real distinction between mind and body, and the relation between the new philosophy and theology. The objections show that Cartesianism was contested from the beginning, not simply accepted as a new orthodoxy. They also helped define the agenda of early modern philosophy.',
      'Spinoza, Leibniz, Locke, Hume, and Kant all inherit problems from Descartes while refusing parts of his system. Spinoza replaces two created substances with one infinite substance. Leibniz rejects material extension as the ultimate nature of substance and builds a metaphysics of monads. Locke criticizes innate ideas and turns to experience, while still wrestling with substance and personal identity in a post-Cartesian vocabulary. Hume radicalizes doubts about causation and self. Kant says that Hume awakened him, but Kant\'s critical philosophy also responds to the Cartesian problem of how subjectivity and objectivity relate. Descartes begins a conversation partly because later thinkers find his answers inadequate.'
    ],['rationalism','empiricism','epistemology','metaphysics'],['descartes','spinoza','leibniz','locke','hume','kant'],['Meditations on First Philosophy','Objections and Replies']),
    section('misunderstandings','Common misunderstandings and interpretive tensions',[
      'Several misunderstandings make Descartes easier to dismiss than to read. He did not simply say that nothing exists except his mind. He did not intend doubt as a lifestyle. He did not reduce all knowledge to private feelings. He did not think the senses are useless; he thought they are unreliable as foundations for metaphysics and physics unless disciplined by reason. Nor is the cogito a triumphant celebration of isolated individualism in the modern cultural sense. It is a minimal point of certainty discovered under an artificial condition of doubt.',
      'The genuine tensions are more interesting. Descartes wants a philosophy of pure intellectual clarity, but human life appears as a union of mind and body that resists clear separation. He wants science secured by metaphysics, but his metaphysical proofs remain disputed. He criticizes scholastic obscurity, yet some of his own causal and representational principles require inherited metaphysical assumptions. He makes the thinking self central, but he also needs God to guarantee the route beyond the self. Reading Descartes well means neither treating him as a solved museum piece nor blaming him for every later dualism. It means seeing how his search for certainty created a new map of philosophical problems.'
    ],['epistemology','philosophy-of-mind','metaphysics'],['descartes','locke','hume','kant'],['Meditations on First Philosophy']),
    section('reading-strategy','A reading strategy for Descartes',[
      'A good route begins with the Discourse on Method, especially its autobiographical presentation of intellectual dissatisfaction, method, provisional morality, and the link between mathematics and inquiry. Then read the Meditations slowly, one meditation at a time, tracking what has and has not been established at each stage. The First Meditation removes confidence; the Second finds the thinking self; the Third and Fifth argue for God; the Fourth explains error; the Sixth restores body and external world while distinguishing mind from body. It helps to read the Objections and Replies selectively, because Descartes\' answers clarify what he thought the stakes were.',
      'After the Meditations, read selections from Principles of Philosophy for the systematic project, then the Passions of the Soul to see how embodiment, emotion, and ethics complicate the metaphysical picture. Keep three questions in view. First, what does Descartes think can be known by reason alone? Second, how does he move from certainty about thought to trust in a world beyond thought? Third, where do later philosophers accept his problem but reject his solution? Those questions make Descartes less a slogan about "I think" and more a working laboratory for modern epistemology, metaphysics, philosophy of mind, and science.'
    ],['rationalism','epistemology','philosophy-of-mind'],['descartes','spinoza','leibniz','locke','hume','kant'],['Discourse on Method','Meditations on First Philosophy','Principles of Philosophy','Passions of the Soul'])
  ],
  spinoza:[
    section('overview','A philosophy of one substance and liberated understanding',[
      'Spinoza is one of the most radical philosophers of the early modern period because he rejects the picture of reality as divided between a creator God, created minds, and created bodies standing in external causal relations. In the Ethics, he argues that there is only one substance, God or Nature, with infinitely many attributes, of which human beings know thought and extension. Individual minds and bodies are not independent substances. They are finite modes, limited expressions of the same infinite reality. This metaphysics transforms theology, psychology, ethics, and politics at once.',
      'The aim is not cold system-building for its own sake. Spinoza wants to understand how human beings can move from bondage to freedom. We are usually governed by partial knowledge, passive emotions, social imagination, fear, hope, resentment, and superstition. Freedom does not mean uncaused choice floating outside nature. It means becoming more active by understanding the causes that determine us and by forming adequate ideas. The famous geometrical style can look forbidding, but beneath it is a therapeutic project: to replace confused dependence on fortune with intellectual love, shared rational life, and greater power to act.'
    ],['rationalism','metaphysics','ethics','philosophy-of-religion'],['spinoza','descartes','leibniz','hume','kant'],['Ethics','Theological-Political Treatise']),
    section('historical-setting','Amsterdam, exile, and the Dutch context',[
      'Spinoza was born in 1632 into the Portuguese-Jewish community of Amsterdam. That community had been shaped by exile, forced conversion, return to Judaism, commerce, multilingual learning, and the relative toleration of the Dutch Republic. Relative toleration did not mean complete freedom. Communities defended their boundaries, religious authorities remained powerful, and political conflict between republican and more authoritarian tendencies could become violent. Spinoza\'s thought emerges from this charged environment of commercial modernity, scriptural debate, confessional anxiety, and new science.',
      'In 1656 Spinoza was excommunicated from the Amsterdam Jewish community. The exact combination of reasons remains debated, but his later writings make clear why his views were alarming. He denied a personal providential God in the usual sense, treated scripture historically, rejected miracles as violations of nature, and opposed religious control over philosophy. After the ban he lived modestly, worked as a lens grinder, corresponded with learned Europeans, and published cautiously. His political and religious arguments were not academic abstractions. They responded to the real dangers of communities that use fear and authority to govern thought.'
    ],['political-philosophy','philosophy-of-religion','rationalism'],['spinoza','descartes'],['Theological-Political Treatise','Ethics']),
    section('cartesian-background','From Cartesian problems to Spinozist reconstruction',[
      'Spinoza learned deeply from Descartes but refused the structure of Cartesian dualism. Descartes had distinguished thinking substance and extended substance, while also relying on God as creator and guarantor. Spinoza saw instability in that picture. If substance is what exists in itself and is conceived through itself, then created finite substances appear not to be genuine substances at all. If mind and body are really distinct substances, their interaction becomes obscure. Spinoza\'s answer is to deny that minds and bodies are separate substances. Thought and extension are attributes of one infinite substance.',
      'This reconstruction preserves something Cartesian and overturns something Cartesian. Like Descartes, Spinoza wants clear rational understanding and a systematic account of reality. Unlike Descartes, he removes the metaphysical gap between God and nature, mind and body, will and intellect. The result is often described as monism, but the term should not flatten the view. Spinoza does not say that all things are one featureless blob. Reality is infinitely expressive, ordered through attributes and modes. Human beings are finite patterns within that order, not exceptions to it.'
    ],['rationalism','metaphysics','philosophy-of-mind'],['spinoza','descartes','leibniz'],['Ethics','Principles of Cartesian Philosophy']),
    section('substance-attributes-modes','Substance, attributes, and modes',[
      'The opening of the Ethics defines substance, attribute, mode, God, freedom, and eternity with deliberate precision. A substance is in itself and conceived through itself. An attribute is what the intellect perceives as constituting the essence of substance. A mode is an affection or modification of substance, something that exists in and is conceived through another. God is an absolutely infinite being, a substance consisting of infinite attributes. From these definitions and axioms Spinoza argues that only one substance exists and that everything else follows from its nature.',
      'This is not creation in time by divine choice. Spinoza\'s God does not decide among possible worlds like a monarch choosing a plan. Things follow from the necessity of divine nature. This necessity is one reason many readers accused him of atheism, while others saw him as offering an austere form of philosophical religion. He identifies God with Nature, but "Nature" here has two senses: natura naturans, nature as active self-expressing cause, and natura naturata, nature as the whole order of modes that follow from that cause. The distinction lets Spinoza speak of God as cause without imagining God as a separate person outside the world.'
    ],['metaphysics','philosophy-of-religion','rationalism'],['spinoza','descartes','leibniz'],['Ethics']),
    section('mind-body-parallelism','Mind, body, and the order of ideas',[
      'Spinoza\'s account of mind and body is sometimes called parallelism, though the label can mislead if it suggests two separate tracks coordinated from outside. The order and connection of ideas is the same as the order and connection of things. The human mind is the idea of the human body. Mental and bodily events are not two substances interacting; they are one finite mode understood under different attributes, thought and extension. When the body is affected by other bodies, the mind has ideas corresponding to those bodily affections.',
      'This view dissolves the Cartesian interaction problem by rejecting its premise. It also changes self-knowledge. We do not begin with a transparent soul fully aware of itself. The mind knows itself through ideas of the body\'s affections, and many of those ideas are partial and confused because the body is affected by external bodies in ways we do not adequately understand. Human consciousness is therefore embedded, relational, and often inadequate. Spinoza is not reducing mind to body; he is refusing to treat either attribute as the ultimate explanation of the other.'
    ],['philosophy-of-mind','metaphysics','rationalism'],['spinoza','descartes','leibniz'],['Ethics']),
    section('knowledge-imagination-reason','Imagination, reason, and intuitive knowledge',[
      'Spinoza distinguishes kinds of knowledge. The first kind, often linked to imagination, arises from sensory experience, signs, hearsay, and fragmentary encounters with things. It is not worthless, but it is the source of error when partial images are treated as adequate understanding. The second kind, reason, grasps common notions and necessary relations shared by things. It gives more stable and adequate knowledge because it understands what follows from the nature of bodies and minds. The third kind, intuitive knowledge, understands particular things through their dependence on God or Nature.',
      'These levels are ethically important. Human bondage is sustained by inadequate ideas: we take our local perspective as the measure of reality, imagine purposes where there are causes, and hate what we do not understand. Reason does not remove emotion by scolding it. It changes what the mind can do. Adequate ideas are active; they express our power of understanding rather than our passive exposure to external causes. Intuitive knowledge intensifies this activity by seeing finite things as expressions of the infinite order. For Spinoza, knowing more adequately is already a form of living more freely.'
    ],['epistemology','metaphysics','ethics'],['spinoza','descartes','hume'],['Ethics']),
    section('conatus-affects','Conatus, affects, and bondage',[
      'Spinoza\'s moral psychology begins with conatus: each thing strives to persevere in its being. In human life this striving appears through desire, appetite, emotion, and the effort to increase one\'s power of acting. Joy is a passage to greater perfection or power; sadness is a passage to lesser power. Love and hate are joy and sadness accompanied by the idea of an external cause. This analysis can sound mechanical, but it is designed to explain the emotional logic by which people become dependent, reactive, and vulnerable to manipulation.',
      'Bondage occurs when we are governed by passive affects, emotions whose causes we do not adequately understand and whose direction is largely determined by external forces. A person can know abstractly that anger is destructive and still be moved by resentment if the underlying imaginative associations remain powerful. Spinoza therefore rejects moralism that simply blames people for being weak. He wants to understand how affects are caused, how they combine, how they are intensified by social imitation, and how more active affects can counter passive ones. Ethics becomes a causal therapy of desire.'
    ],['ethics','philosophy-of-mind','rationalism'],['spinoza','hume'],['Ethics']),
    section('freedom-necessity','Freedom through necessity',[
      'Spinoza denies libertarian free will. Human beings think they are free because they are conscious of their desires and choices but ignorant of the causes that determine them. This claim is often mistaken for fatalism, as if Spinoza believed effort is pointless. His view is different. Everything is determined, but some things are determined through their own nature more adequately than through external compulsion. A free person acts from the necessity of their nature as understood by reason; an unfree person is pushed and pulled by causes they grasp only confusedly.',
      'Freedom, then, is not exemption from nature but participation in nature through understanding. When I understand why envy, fear, or superstition arises, I am not magically removed from causal order. I become able to form ideas and habits that express more of my own rational power. Spinoza\'s free person is not emotionless. The free person is moved by active joys, generosity, firmness, and intellectual love. The hard question is whether this account preserves enough of responsibility, deliberation, and moral criticism. Spinoza\'s answer is that praise, blame, law, and education are themselves causal practices that can increase or decrease human power.'
    ],['ethics','metaphysics','philosophy-of-mind'],['spinoza','hume','kant'],['Ethics']),
    section('god-religion-scripture','God, scripture, and the critique of superstition',[
      'The Theological-Political Treatise argues that scripture should be read historically, with attention to language, audience, genre, transmission, and practical aim. Spinoza denies that prophets were philosophers teaching metaphysics through hidden codes. Their authority concerns obedience, justice, and charity rather than speculative knowledge. Miracles are not violations of natural order, because nothing can happen outside the necessity of divine nature. Reports of miracles reveal the limits of human understanding and the imaginative form of popular religion.',
      'This approach was explosive because it separated philosophy from theology and limited religious authority over inquiry. Spinoza did not simply despise religion. He distinguished superstition, which thrives on fear and ignorance, from a practical piety centered on justice and love of neighbor. He thought the state should protect freedom of philosophizing because coercion over belief produces hypocrisy, conflict, and intellectual stagnation. His biblical criticism became a landmark in modern thought, not because every historical claim was final, but because he treated sacred texts as humanly mediated documents without denying their ethical force for communities.'
    ],['philosophy-of-religion','political-philosophy','epistemology'],['spinoza'],['Theological-Political Treatise']),
    section('politics-democracy','Politics, democracy, and freedom of thought',[
      'Spinoza\'s political philosophy begins from human beings as they are, not as moralists wish them to be. People are moved by desire, fear, hope, imitation, ambition, and reason in varying degrees. A stable political order must channel these affects rather than pretend they can be abolished. Natural right is coextensive with power: each thing has as much right as it has power to act. Civil society arises not by escaping nature but by organizing common power in ways that provide security and allow more rational life.',
      'Spinoza favors forms of government that preserve freedom of thought and distribute power broadly, with democracy often appearing as the most natural regime because it best expresses collective power. Yet his politics is not sentimental. He knows that crowds can be superstitious and volatile, and he analyzes how authorities exploit fear. The central political question is how institutions can reduce domination, secure peace, and permit minds to develop. Freedom of speech is not a decorative liberal preference for Spinoza. It is a condition of philosophical and civic health because thought cannot be commanded in the same way bodies can be restrained.'
    ],['political-philosophy','ethics','philosophy-of-religion'],['spinoza','locke','hume'],['Theological-Political Treatise','Political Treatise']),
    section('ethics-geometry-style','The geometrical style and its purpose',[
      'The Ethics is written in definitions, axioms, propositions, demonstrations, corollaries, and scholia. The style can feel alien, especially when it treats emotions with the calm structure of geometry. Spinoza uses the form to display necessity. He wants readers to see that metaphysics, psychology, and ethics are not separate opinions but connected consequences. The scholia, appendices, and prefaces are often more rhetorically direct, revealing the polemical and therapeutic force behind the austere surface.',
      'The style also creates interpretive tension. Does the geometrical method genuinely prove the system, or does it give an appearance of proof to controversial definitions and assumptions? Readers have disagreed from the beginning. A charitable reading does not require pretending that every demonstration compels assent like Euclid. It asks what philosophical discipline the form imposes. Spinoza refuses to treat human beings as a kingdom within a kingdom. By analyzing passions, religion, and politics as natural phenomena, he tries to free us from moral panic and theological exception.'
    ],['rationalism','metaphysics','ethics'],['spinoza','descartes','leibniz'],['Ethics']),
    section('reception-misunderstandings','Reception, misunderstandings, and interpretive disputes',[
      'Spinoza\'s reputation swung between horror and admiration. Many early readers treated him as an atheist, determinist, and enemy of religion. Later German thinkers, Romantic writers, biblical critics, political radicals, and contemporary philosophers found in him a profound alternative to dualism, voluntarist theology, and individualist moralism. His influence reaches debates about secularism, democracy, affect, ecology, embodiment, and the relation between freedom and necessity. He often returns when philosophers seek a non-supernatural account of meaning and ethical transformation.',
      'Common misunderstandings flatten him. "God or Nature" does not mean simply that forests and stars are a personal deity. Determinism does not mean resignation. The denial of free will does not make ethics pointless. The critique of superstition does not erase the social power of religion. The geometric style does not mean the philosophy is bloodless. Real disputes remain: whether Spinoza is best read as atheist, pantheist, panentheist, or something that unsettles those categories; whether his politics is democratic enough by modern standards; whether his account of affects can handle individuality; whether intellectual love is accessible to ordinary life or only to rare philosophical understanding.'
    ],['rationalism','political-philosophy','philosophy-of-religion','ethics'],['spinoza','leibniz','hume','kant'],['Ethics','Theological-Political Treatise']),
    section('reading-strategy','A reading strategy for Spinoza',[
      'Begin with the Appendix to Part I of the Ethics before trying to master the opening demonstrations. The Appendix attacks teleology, superstition, and the projection of human purposes onto nature, giving a clear sense of the problem Spinoza wants to solve. Then read Part III on the affects and Part IV on bondage, because the ethical urgency of the system becomes visible there. Return to Part I with the question of why such a metaphysics would matter for freedom. Read slowly, following definitions and propositions, but do not ignore the scholia where Spinoza often speaks with greatest practical force.',
      'Pair the Ethics with selections from the Theological-Political Treatise on prophecy, miracles, interpretation, and freedom of philosophizing. This prevents a narrow view of Spinoza as only a metaphysician. The guiding questions should be: what changes if God is not outside nature, what changes if the mind is the idea of the body, and what changes if freedom means adequate understanding rather than uncaused choice? Those questions make Spinoza\'s system less intimidating and more recognizable as a sustained attempt to cure fear, confusion, and servitude through understanding.'
    ],['rationalism','metaphysics','ethics','political-philosophy'],['spinoza','descartes','leibniz','hume'],['Ethics','Theological-Political Treatise'])
  ],
  leibniz:[
    section('overview','Harmony, plurality, and the rational order of things',[
      'Leibniz is the early modern philosopher of abundance. Where Descartes seeks certainty through clear foundations and Spinoza builds a system from one infinite substance, Leibniz imagines reality as an ordered plurality of simple substances, each expressing the whole universe from its own point of view. He combines mathematics, logic, metaphysics, theology, physics, law, history, diplomacy, and plans for academies and calculating machines. His philosophical style is correspondingly scattered across essays, letters, drafts, and occasional works rather than one final book that says everything.',
      'The central impulse is rational intelligibility. Leibniz thinks reality is governed by principles: identity, noncontradiction, sufficient reason, continuity, the identity of indiscernibles, and the choice of the best. Nothing is brute in the deepest sense. Yet this rationalism does not produce a flat uniform world. It produces a world of perspectives, degrees, organisms, forces, perceptions, and harmonies. His metaphysics can look fantastically strange, but it is trying to solve concrete problems left by Descartes and Spinoza: what substances are, how mind and body relate, how freedom fits with divine foreknowledge, how science can use mathematics without reducing living beings to dead extension, and why this world exists at all.'
    ],['rationalism','metaphysics','epistemology','philosophy-of-religion'],['leibniz','descartes','spinoza','locke','hume','kant','aristotle','aquinas'],['Discourse on Metaphysics','Monadology','Theodicy']),
    section('life-context-projects','Life, correspondence, and encyclopedic ambition',[
      'Leibniz was born in Leipzig in 1646 and lived as a scholar, jurist, court counselor, diplomat, librarian, mathematician, and philosophical correspondent. He worked for German courts, traveled to Paris and elsewhere, engaged with leading scientists and theologians, and pursued projects for church reunion, legal reform, scholarly academies, universal languages, and mechanical calculation. This practical world matters for understanding his philosophy. He did not imagine reason as a private retreat. He wanted rational methods to organize knowledge, reduce conflict, and improve institutions.',
      'Because much of Leibniz\'s work remained unpublished or dispersed in correspondence, his philosophy can seem like a set of brilliant fragments. The Discourse on Metaphysics, New Essays on Human Understanding, Theodicy, Principles of Nature and Grace, and Monadology each present different gateways. Letters to Arnauld, De Volder, Clarke, and many others show him adjusting arguments for particular interlocutors. Reading Leibniz therefore requires attention to occasion. He is often trying to reconcile opponents by showing that each has grasped part of the truth at the wrong level of analysis.'
    ],['rationalism','philosophy-of-science','political-philosophy'],['leibniz','locke'],['Discourse on Metaphysics','New Essays on Human Understanding','Monadology','Leibniz-Clarke Correspondence']),
    section('principles-reason','The principles of reason',[
      'Leibniz\'s philosophy is organized by several great principles. The principle of noncontradiction governs necessary truths: a proposition cannot be both true and false in the same respect. The principle of sufficient reason says that nothing happens and no truth obtains without a reason why it is so and not otherwise, even if finite minds do not know that reason. The identity of indiscernibles says that no two distinct things can be exactly alike in every respect, because there would be no sufficient reason for their distinction. The principle of continuity resists abrupt unexplained gaps in nature.',
      'These principles give Leibniz his characteristic confidence and his characteristic difficulties. If every truth has a reason, then contingency, freedom, and evil must be explained without making the world arbitrary. If distinct things must differ internally, then space cannot be a container in which identical objects are merely placed at different coordinates. If nature does not make leaps, then physical and biological phenomena should be understood through gradual transitions and nested complexity. Leibniz uses rational principles as engines of discovery, but critics ask whether they legislate reality too strongly from the armchair.'
    ],['epistemology','metaphysics','rationalism'],['leibniz','descartes','spinoza','hume','kant'],['Discourse on Metaphysics','Monadology','Leibniz-Clarke Correspondence']),
    section('truth-concepts','Truth, concepts, and contingency',[
      'Leibniz holds that in every true affirmative proposition, the predicate is contained in the subject. At first this can sound as if all truths are merely analytic and therefore necessary. Leibniz\'s actual position is subtler. Necessary truths can be analyzed by finite steps into identities. Contingent truths also have reasons, but their analysis would proceed infinitely because they involve the whole order of the world. Caesar crossing the Rubicon is contained in the complete concept of Caesar, but understanding that complete concept would require understanding the entire universe that Caesar expresses.',
      'This theory connects logic with metaphysics. An individual is not a bare thing that receives accidental labels from outside. It has a complete concept that includes its relations, history, and place in the world. Critics worry that this threatens freedom: if all my actions are contained in my complete concept, could I do otherwise? Leibniz answers by distinguishing certainty from necessity. Free actions are certain because God knows and chooses the complete world, but they are not necessary in the way mathematical truths are. Whether this distinction fully satisfies the worry remains one of the main tensions in his system.'
    ],['epistemology','metaphysics','rationalism'],['leibniz','spinoza','kant'],['Discourse on Metaphysics','Theodicy']),
    section('monads','Monads and the rejection of bare extension',[
      'Leibniz\'s mature metaphysics replaces extended material substance with monads. A monad is a simple, non-extended substance with perception and appetite. Because it has no parts, it cannot be generated or destroyed by ordinary physical division. Because it has no windows, no created monad literally receives causal influence from another. Each monad unfolds its states from its own internal principle, while expressing the entire universe from a particular point of view. Bodies are well-founded phenomena grounded in organized aggregates of monads.',
      'This view responds to problems in Cartesian physics. If matter is only extension, then it seems infinitely divisible and passive, unable to provide genuine unity or force. Leibniz thinks real substances must be units, and genuine units cannot be extended aggregates. The language of perception should not be confused with conscious awareness. Every monad perceives in the broad sense of representing plurality in unity, but only some have apperception or reflective consciousness. The result is a world alive with degrees of perception, not a universe split between dead matter and a few thinking souls.'
    ],['metaphysics','philosophy-of-mind','rationalism'],['leibniz','descartes','spinoza','aristotle'],['Monadology','Principles of Nature and Grace']),
    section('preestablished-harmony','Pre-established harmony and mind-body union',[
      'If monads do not causally interact, how do events coordinate? Leibniz\'s answer is pre-established harmony. God creates each monad with an internal law of development that perfectly corresponds to every other monad. Mind and body do not push each other; they agree like synchronized clocks because their histories are harmonized from the beginning. When I decide to raise my arm and my arm rises, the mental and bodily sequences correspond without direct causal transfer between substances.',
      'This proposal is easy to mock, but it solves problems Leibniz thought were otherwise intractable. Descartes could not adequately explain interaction between thinking and extended substances. Occasionalism made God the direct cause of each coordination, threatening to turn created things into passive occasions. Spinoza eliminated created substances into one substance. Leibniz preserves created plurality, real activity, and lawful correspondence. The cost is high: many readers find the absence of inter-monadic causation counterintuitive. The benefit is a metaphysics in which each finite being has an internal principle and the universe forms a rationally coordinated whole.'
    ],['philosophy-of-mind','metaphysics','rationalism'],['leibniz','descartes','spinoza'],['Monadology','Discourse on Metaphysics']),
    section('best-world-theodicy','The best possible world and the problem of evil',[
      'Leibniz\'s claim that this is the best of all possible worlds is often caricatured as cheerful denial of suffering. His actual theodicy begins from divine wisdom, goodness, and power. God understands all possible worlds and chooses to actualize the one with the greatest balance of perfection, order, variety, and intelligibility. Evil is permitted, not because it is good in itself, but because a world containing certain evils may be inseparable from greater goods or from the best total order available among compossible possibilities.',
      'The theory faces obvious pressure. Does appealing to the whole order trivialize actual pain? Can finite minds responsibly claim that every evil is necessary for the best? Does the concept of the best world make sense if values are plural and suffering is concrete? Leibniz distinguishes metaphysical evil, the limitation involved in finite being; physical evil, suffering; and moral evil, sin. He also insists that God does not will evil as evil. Still, the Lisbon earthquake and later critics made Leibnizian optimism a target. The philosophical issue is not whether Leibniz lacked compassion, but whether rational explanation can coexist with protest against evil.'
    ],['philosophy-of-religion','metaphysics','ethics'],['leibniz','spinoza','aquinas','hume'],['Theodicy','Monadology']),
    section('freedom-grace','Freedom, foreknowledge, and moral responsibility',[
      'Leibniz wants to preserve both rational determination and genuine freedom. A free action, for him, is spontaneous, intelligent, and contingent. It arises from the agent\'s own internal principle rather than external compulsion; it is guided by reasons; and its contrary remains possible in the sense that it involves no contradiction. God foreknows the action because God knows the complete concept of the individual and the world chosen, but foreknowledge does not impose necessity in the same way that a geometrical theorem is necessary.',
      'This is a delicate balance. If every action is included in the complete concept of the person God creates, then responsibility seems threatened. Leibniz answers that the person\'s action still flows from that person, not from coercion. He also uses the idea of possible worlds to say that God chooses a world in which free creatures act, rather than separately forcing each act. Critics ask whether this merely relocates the problem to divine choice. The debate shows how Leibniz\'s metaphysics turns theology, logic, and ethics into one problem: how can a fully intelligible world include agents who are not puppets?'
    ],['ethics','metaphysics','philosophy-of-religion'],['leibniz','spinoza','aquinas','kant'],['Theodicy','Discourse on Metaphysics']),
    section('knowledge-innate-ideas','Knowledge, innate ideas, and the debate with Locke',[
      'Leibniz\'s New Essays on Human Understanding replies to Locke\'s Essay. Locke had criticized innate ideas and emphasized experience as the source of human understanding. Leibniz answers with the image of the mind as veined marble rather than a blank tablet. Experience is necessary, but it does not write on a wholly passive surface. The mind has dispositions, structures, and tendencies that make certain truths discoverable. Necessary truths, especially in logic and mathematics, cannot be derived from sensory experience alone because experience shows what happens, not what must be.',
      'The dispute is not simply rationalism versus empiricism in cartoon form. Leibniz accepts that sense experience occasions much of our knowledge and that human cognition develops over time. His point is that experience must be interpreted by powers already belonging to the mind. He also introduces petites perceptions, tiny perceptions below the threshold of awareness, to explain continuity in mental life. Conscious thought is only the surface of a deeper perceptual activity. In this respect Leibniz anticipates later questions about unconscious mental processes while remaining committed to a strongly rational order.'
    ],['epistemology','rationalism','empiricism','philosophy-of-mind'],['leibniz','locke','hume','kant'],['New Essays on Human Understanding','Essay Concerning Human Understanding']),
    section('science-force-space','Science, force, space, and the debate with Newtonians',[
      'Leibniz was a major mathematician and co-inventor of calculus independently of Newton, though the priority dispute became bitter. In physics, he criticized the Cartesian reduction of matter to extension and emphasized force. His dynamics treats activity as fundamental to bodies, though his metaphysics ultimately grounds bodies in monads rather than in extended substance. He also contributed to mechanics, logic, probability, engineering projects, and the dream of symbolic calculation. His scientific work is not a side interest; it expresses the conviction that reality is intelligible through formal relations.',
      'The correspondence with Samuel Clarke, defending Newtonian positions, reveals Leibniz\'s philosophy of space and time. Leibniz rejects absolute space as an independent container. Space is an order of coexistences; time is an order of successions. If two worlds differed only by being shifted in absolute space, there would be no sufficient reason for God to choose one over the other. This relational view connects the identity of indiscernibles with theology and physics. The debate anticipates later philosophy of space and time, even though later science changed the terms.'
    ],['philosophy-of-science','metaphysics','rationalism'],['leibniz','descartes','kant'],['Leibniz-Clarke Correspondence','Monadology']),
    section('politics-ecumenism','Law, politics, and projects of reconciliation',[
      'Leibniz\'s practical work in law, diplomacy, and church reunion is sometimes separated from his metaphysics, but the separation is misleading. He wanted reason to reduce conflict by finding deeper principles that could reconcile partial perspectives. His ecumenical projects sought forms of Christian reunion; his legal and political writings aimed at order and reform; his plans for academies imagined collaborative knowledge production. These projects can appear over-ambitious, but they show how his metaphysics of harmony becomes a social ideal.',
      'The danger is that reconciliation may smooth over real conflict or underestimate power. Leibniz often preferred synthesis to rupture, and his courtly world encouraged negotiation among elites. Yet his commitment to plurality within order remains philosophically significant. He does not imagine truth as a single human standpoint conquering all others. Each monad expresses the whole from its perspective; each discipline and tradition may contain partial insight. The political and intellectual task is to coordinate perspectives without collapsing them into sameness.'
    ],['political-philosophy','philosophy-of-religion','rationalism'],['leibniz'],['Theodicy','Discourse on Metaphysics']),
    section('influence-misunderstandings','Influence, misunderstandings, and interpretive tensions',[
      'Leibniz influenced Wolffian rationalism, German Enlightenment philosophy, Kant, later logic, metaphysics, philosophy of science, and theories of possible worlds. Kant\'s critical philosophy can be read partly as an attempt to discipline Leibnizian rationalism by asking what conditions make experience possible for finite knowers. Modern modal logic and analytic metaphysics return to Leibnizian themes of possible worlds, identity, necessity, and sufficient reason, though often in forms he would not fully recognize.',
      'Misunderstandings are common. Monads are not tiny physical atoms. Pre-established harmony is not simple denial that mind and body correspond. The best possible world is not the claim that every event is pleasant or that injustice should be accepted passively. Innate ideas are not fully formed sentences sitting in the mind from birth. The real tensions are harder: whether sufficient reason overreaches, whether contingency survives complete concepts, whether evil can be integrated into rational order without moral distortion, and whether a world without created causal interaction can still make sense of community and responsibility.'
    ],['rationalism','metaphysics','epistemology','philosophy-of-religion'],['leibniz','locke','hume','kant'],['Monadology','Theodicy','New Essays on Human Understanding']),
    section('reading-strategy','A reading strategy for Leibniz',[
      'Do not begin by trying to force all of Leibniz into one diagram. Start with the Monadology for a compressed overview, but treat it as a map rather than a substitute for the terrain. Then read the Discourse on Metaphysics and correspondence with Arnauld to see complete concepts, substance, and freedom under pressure. Read selections from the New Essays alongside Locke to understand the epistemological debate. Use the Theodicy for evil and freedom, and the Leibniz-Clarke correspondence for space, time, and sufficient reason.',
      'As you read, track Leibniz\'s repeated strategy: he accepts a problem from an opponent, distinguishes levels of analysis, and tries to preserve the truth in each side through a more comprehensive principle. Ask what work each principle does. Why does sufficient reason matter here? Why must substances be unities? Why is harmony preferable to interaction? Why does possibility require compossibility? This approach makes Leibniz less like a collector of bizarre doctrines and more like a philosopher trying to show that plurality, science, theology, and freedom can belong to one rational order.'
    ],['rationalism','metaphysics','epistemology','philosophy-of-science'],['leibniz','descartes','spinoza','locke','kant'],['Monadology','Discourse on Metaphysics','New Essays on Human Understanding','Theodicy','Leibniz-Clarke Correspondence'])
  ],
  locke:[
    section('overview','Experience, limits, and the politics of reasonable liberty',[
      'Locke is a central figure of empiricism, liberal political philosophy, and early modern debates about religious toleration. His Essay Concerning Human Understanding asks what the human mind can know by examining the origin, extent, and limits of ideas. Instead of beginning with innate principles or metaphysical certainty, Locke studies the materials of understanding as they arise from sensation and reflection. He wants to clear away pretended knowledge so that inquiry can become more modest, useful, and secure.',
      'The same temper appears in his political and religious writings. Locke is not a skeptic who thinks nothing can be known, nor a radical democrat in the modern sense, nor a simple celebrant of private preference. He seeks standards for responsible belief, legitimate government, property, consent, toleration, and education under conditions of human fallibility. His influence is immense, but his legacy is morally mixed. The language of natural rights and limited government sits beside exclusions, colonial entanglements, and assumptions about property that later readers must scrutinize carefully.'
    ],['empiricism','epistemology','political-philosophy','philosophy-of-religion'],['locke','descartes','leibniz','hume','kant','aristotle','aquinas'],['Essay Concerning Human Understanding','Two Treatises of Government','A Letter Concerning Toleration']),
    section('historical-setting','Civil conflict, science, and Restoration England',[
      'Locke was born in 1632, the same year as Spinoza, and grew up in a Britain marked by civil war, republican experiment, restoration of monarchy, religious conflict, and disputes over authority. These events shaped his political philosophy. Questions about consent, resistance, toleration, church power, property, and executive authority were not abstract puzzles. They were matters of institutional survival and personal danger. Locke\'s association with the Earl of Shaftesbury connected him to opposition politics, and he spent time in exile in the Dutch Republic before the Glorious Revolution.',
      'The intellectual setting was also changing. Locke was close to physicians, natural philosophers, and the world of the Royal Society. He admired experimental inquiry and distrusted systems that outran evidence. This does not mean he rejected metaphysics entirely. The Essay discusses substance, identity, power, freedom, and God. But Locke\'s guiding question is often practical: what can creatures like us responsibly claim to know, and where should we accept probability rather than certainty? His philosophy belongs to a culture learning to value observation, testimony, experiment, and public debate while still wrestling with theology and political order.'
    ],['empiricism','political-philosophy','philosophy-of-science'],['locke','hume'],['Essay Concerning Human Understanding','Two Treatises of Government']),
    section('anti-innatism','The critique of innate ideas',[
      'Locke opens the Essay by attacking innate principles and innate ideas. He argues that there is no universal consent to supposedly innate truths, since children and many adults do not consciously possess them. Even if a truth were universally accepted, that would not prove it was innate. The mind comes to be furnished with ideas through experience: sensation gives ideas of external objects, while reflection gives ideas of the mind\'s own operations, such as perceiving, willing, doubting, comparing, and remembering.',
      'This critique is sometimes oversimplified. Locke does not deny that human beings have natural capacities. He denies that specific speculative and practical principles are stamped on the mind as known from birth. His target includes philosophical rationalists, but also theological and political authorities who appeal to supposedly innate truths in ways that bypass examination. By asking how ideas actually enter the mind, Locke shifts attention from inherited certainty to cognitive development. Leibniz\'s later response argues that Locke underestimates the mind\'s active structures, but even that response shows how decisively Locke set the agenda.'
    ],['epistemology','empiricism','rationalism'],['locke','descartes','leibniz'],['Essay Concerning Human Understanding','New Essays on Human Understanding']),
    section('ideas-simple-complex','Simple ideas, complex ideas, and abstraction',[
      'Locke\'s basic unit of analysis is the idea, whatever is immediately before the mind when a person thinks. Simple ideas arrive passively through sensation or reflection: colors, sounds, solidity, motion, pleasure, pain, willing, and so on. The mind cannot invent a simple idea entirely from nothing. It can, however, combine, compare, and abstract from simple ideas to form complex ideas. Modes, substances, and relations are different kinds of complex ideas. This framework lets Locke explain how human thought becomes rich without appealing to innate content.',
      'Abstraction is especially important. The mind can form general ideas by leaving out particular circumstances and using words to stand for many things. Generality belongs not to mysterious universal objects floating outside the mind but to the use of signs and abstract ideas. This position helps Locke explain classification and language, but it also raises problems. Are abstract ideas psychologically plausible? Can the idea of a triangle that is neither equilateral, nor scalene, nor isosceles make sense? Berkeley later attacks Locke on this point. The problem shows that empiricism must explain not only how ideas begin, but how general thought works.'
    ],['epistemology','empiricism','philosophy-of-mind'],['locke','hume','leibniz'],['Essay Concerning Human Understanding']),
    section('qualities-substance','Primary qualities, secondary qualities, and substance',[
      'Locke distinguishes primary qualities, such as solidity, extension, figure, motion, rest, and number, from secondary qualities, such as colors, sounds, tastes, and smells. Primary qualities are inseparable from bodies and resemble something in the objects. Secondary qualities are powers in objects to produce ideas in us through their primary qualities. The distinction fits the mechanistic science of the age: the world described by physics differs from the world as it appears in ordinary sensory experience.',
      'Substance is more difficult. We group qualities together and suppose there is some support in which they inhere, but Locke famously says our idea of substance in general is obscure. We know collections of observable qualities and powers, not the inner essence that makes a thing what it is. This modesty is epistemologically important. Locke does not deny that substances exist; he denies that we possess clear knowledge of their real essences in most cases. Natural classification therefore depends heavily on nominal essences, the abstract ideas and names by which we sort things, rather than transparent access to nature\'s inner constitution.'
    ],['epistemology','metaphysics','philosophy-of-science','empiricism'],['locke','descartes','hume','kant'],['Essay Concerning Human Understanding']),
    section('knowledge-probability','Knowledge, probability, and the conduct of understanding',[
      'Locke defines knowledge as the perception of the agreement or disagreement of ideas. This can occur intuitively, demonstratively, or sensitively. Intuitive knowledge is immediate, as when the mind perceives that white is not black. Demonstrative knowledge proceeds through intermediate ideas, as in mathematics and some arguments about God. Sensitive knowledge concerns the existence of particular external things, though Locke treats it as less perfect than intuition or demonstration. Much of ordinary life and science, however, operates under probability rather than certainty.',
      'This emphasis on probability is not a weakness in Locke\'s eyes. Human beings are finite. We often must act on testimony, experience, analogy, and degrees of evidence. The responsible mind proportions assent to evidence. Locke\'s concern with enthusiasm, dogmatism, and unexamined authority arises here. People frequently mistake the strength of their conviction for the strength of their evidence. The Conduct of the Understanding continues this practical epistemology by emphasizing intellectual habits, fair-mindedness, and the need to examine how education, party, and custom shape belief.'
    ],['epistemology','empiricism','philosophy-of-science'],['locke','hume','kant'],['Essay Concerning Human Understanding','Of the Conduct of the Understanding']),
    section('personal-identity','Personal identity and consciousness',[
      'Locke\'s chapter on identity distinguishes the identity of masses of matter, living organisms, human beings, and persons. A person is a thinking intelligent being that can consider itself as itself across time. Personal identity consists not in sameness of soul-substance or sameness of body, but in continuity of consciousness, especially memory. If consciousness can extend backward to a past action or thought, then the same person is present for purposes of responsibility.',
      'The view was revolutionary and controversial. It separates personhood from metaphysical substance and connects it to forensic concerns: praise, blame, reward, punishment, and ownership of actions. But memory-based identity faces puzzles. What if memory is interrupted? What if a person falsely remembers? What about the famous later objection in which an old general remembers being a brave officer, and the officer remembers being a child, but the old general does not remember the childhood? Locke\'s account opened a field of debate because it made identity depend on psychological continuity rather than a hidden substance.'
    ],['philosophy-of-mind','epistemology','metaphysics'],['locke','hume'],['Essay Concerning Human Understanding']),
    section('freedom-will','Freedom, will, and uneasiness',[
      'Locke rejects the question "Is the will free?" as confused. Freedom belongs to agents, not to the will considered as a separate faculty. A person is free when they have the power to do or forbear an action according to preference or thought. The will itself is a power of preferring, and asking whether the will is free risks asking whether a power has another power. This analytic move changes the debate by clarifying terms before defending a doctrine.',
      'Locke also argues that desire, especially uneasiness, moves the will. We are stirred to act by a felt lack or discomfort, not simply by abstract judgment of the greatest good. Yet human beings can suspend the prosecution of desire, examine goods, and reshape priorities. This gives Locke a practical account of moral agency. Freedom is not an uncaused rupture in nature; it involves capacities for suspension, reflection, and self-government. The view sits between strict rationalism and simple impulse psychology, and it influenced later debates over motivation and responsibility.'
    ],['philosophy-of-mind','ethics','empiricism'],['locke','hume','kant'],['Essay Concerning Human Understanding']),
    section('political-authority','Natural rights, consent, and legitimate government',[
      'The Two Treatises of Government attacks patriarchal and absolutist theories of political authority and develops an account of legitimate government grounded in natural equality, rights, consent, and fiduciary power. In the state of nature, human beings are free and equal under natural law, with rights to life, liberty, and estate. Political society arises to remedy inconveniences of the state of nature, especially insecure enforcement of natural law. Government is a trust established to protect rights, and when it systematically betrays that trust, resistance can be justified.',
      'Locke\'s political theory became foundational for liberal constitutionalism, but it should be read with care. Consent is central, yet the mechanisms of tacit consent are contested. Majority rule is necessary once a community is formed, but Locke does not offer modern universal democracy. Natural rights limit government, but the boundaries of inclusion are historically restricted. His defense of resistance is powerful because it denies that rulers own their subjects; its limits appear when one asks who counted as a full rights-bearing participant in the social order he imagined.'
    ],['political-philosophy','ethics'],['locke','hume','kant'],['Two Treatises of Government']),
    section('property-labor-colonialism','Property, labor, and colonial entanglements',[
      'Locke\'s theory of property begins with the claim that the earth is initially given in common, but individuals can appropriate parts of it by mixing their labor with them, provided enough and as good is left for others. Labor makes resources useful and connects them to self-ownership. The introduction of money, by consent, allows unequal accumulation without immediate spoilage. This argument became deeply influential in liberal and capitalist traditions.',
      'It is also one of the most contested parts of Locke. The labor theory can recognize the dignity of productive activity, but it can also justify enclosure and colonial appropriation by treating land not cultivated in European ways as underused. Locke\'s involvement with colonial administration and investment contexts makes this more than an abstract worry. Readers should not detach the theory from imperial history. The philosophical question is whether Locke\'s principles of natural equality and consent can criticize colonial dispossession, or whether his account of improvement and property helped enable it.'
    ],['political-philosophy','ethics'],['locke'],['Two Treatises of Government']),
    section('toleration-religion','Toleration, religion, and the limits of civil power',[
      'A Letter Concerning Toleration argues that civil government exists to secure civil interests such as life, liberty, health, and property, not to save souls by force. Genuine belief cannot be produced by coercion, and persecuting people for religion usually confuses political order with spiritual authority. Churches should be voluntary societies, and the magistrate should not impose disputed doctrines by law. The argument helped shape modern ideas of religious liberty.',
      'Locke\'s toleration has limits. He excludes some groups, and his reasons reflect fears about political loyalty and the social conditions of trust. Those exclusions are philosophically important because they show the boundary of his liberalism. The argument for toleration is not yet a full theory of equal religious citizenship. Still, Locke\'s basic separation between civil interests and salvation challenged coercive religious politics. It also fits his epistemology: because human beings are fallible and belief must answer to evidence and conscience, forced assent is both ineffective and morally dangerous.'
    ],['political-philosophy','philosophy-of-religion','epistemology'],['locke','spinoza'],['A Letter Concerning Toleration','Essay Concerning Human Understanding']),
    section('education-character','Education, habit, and the making of persons',[
      'Locke\'s Some Thoughts Concerning Education reveals a practical side of his philosophy. Character is formed through habit, example, discipline, environment, and the management of desire. He emphasizes health, self-command, curiosity, and the avoidance of servile fear. Education is not merely the transfer of information into an empty mind. It shapes the conduct of understanding and the emotional habits through which a person becomes capable of judgment.',
      'This educational program connects the Essay and the political writings. A society of free people requires citizens capable of proportioning belief to evidence, resisting enthusiasm, keeping promises, and governing desire. Yet the social setting of Locke\'s educational advice is restricted, often aimed at gentlemen and households of status. That limitation should be visible. Locke helps explain how persons are made through practice, but the benefits of such formation were not imagined as equally available to all.'
    ],['epistemology','ethics','political-philosophy'],['locke'],['Some Thoughts Concerning Education','Of the Conduct of the Understanding']),
    section('influence-misunderstandings','Influence, misunderstandings, and interpretive tensions',[
      'Locke\'s influence runs through empiricism, liberal political theory, theories of rights, philosophy of language, personal identity, education, and toleration. Berkeley and Hume transform his empiricism by pressing harder on matter, causation, self, and abstraction. Leibniz replies to him from the rationalist side. Kant inherits the problem of how experience can yield objective knowledge while rejecting both simple empiricism and dogmatic rationalism. Politically, Locke became a source for constitutionalism, revolution, natural rights language, and later debates about property and consent.',
      'Misunderstandings make Locke too simple. The blank slate does not mean human beings lack natural capacities. Empiricism does not mean passive recording of sensations. Liberalism in Locke is not identical with modern egalitarian democracy. Toleration is not unlimited. Property is not merely whatever someone happens to seize. The real tensions concern whether his epistemological modesty can support strong natural rights, whether his theory of consent can legitimate actual states, whether his property theory can be separated from colonialism, and whether personal identity based on consciousness can handle memory failure and social embodiment.'
    ],['empiricism','political-philosophy','epistemology'],['locke','leibniz','hume','kant'],['Essay Concerning Human Understanding','Two Treatises of Government','A Letter Concerning Toleration']),
    section('reading-strategy','A reading strategy for Locke',[
      'Begin the Essay with its purpose in mind: Locke is mapping the limits of understanding so that belief can become more responsible. Read Book I on innate ideas, Book II on ideas and qualities, Book II chapter 27 on identity, and Book IV on knowledge and probability. Do not try to memorize every classification at first. Track the larger movement from experience, to ideas, to language, to the degrees of knowledge and opinion. Then read the Conduct of the Understanding for the practical discipline behind the theory.',
      'For political Locke, read the Second Treatise alongside A Letter Concerning Toleration, not as isolated slogans about property and liberty. Ask who is included, what consent is supposed to do, how natural law is known, why property requires labor, and where toleration stops. Pair Locke with Leibniz for the innate ideas debate and with Hume for the empiricist inheritance. This route makes Locke appear neither as a harmless common-sense philosopher nor as a finished liberal hero, but as a thinker whose moderation produced enduring problems as well as enduring tools.'
    ],['empiricism','epistemology','political-philosophy','philosophy-of-religion'],['locke','leibniz','hume','kant'],['Essay Concerning Human Understanding','Two Treatises of Government','A Letter Concerning Toleration','Of the Conduct of the Understanding'])
  ],
  hume:[
    section('overview','A skeptical naturalist of human understanding',[
      'Hume brings early modern empiricism to its most unsettling form. He asks what the mind actually encounters in experience and what habits lead us beyond what experience strictly gives. The result is not a simple denial of knowledge or a recommendation to distrust everything. Hume is a skeptical naturalist: skeptical because he exposes the limits of reason in causation, induction, selfhood, religion, and morality; naturalist because he explains belief as a human practice rooted in custom, sentiment, imagination, and social life.',
      'His philosophy changes the question from "What can be proven with absolute certainty?" to "How do creatures like us come to believe, judge, act, and live together despite the limits of proof?" That shift made him decisive for Kant, who saw in Hume\'s account of causation a challenge that demanded a new critical philosophy. Hume is also central for moral psychology, political theory, philosophy of religion, aesthetics, history, and economics. His calm prose can hide the radical force of the project: many of the assumptions that hold ordinary reasoning together cannot be justified by the kind of reason philosophers had hoped to use.'
    ],['empiricism','epistemology','ethics','philosophy-of-religion'],['hume','locke','descartes','spinoza','leibniz','kant'],['A Treatise of Human Nature','An Enquiry Concerning Human Understanding','An Enquiry Concerning the Principles of Morals']),
    section('life-context','Enlightenment Scotland and literary ambition',[
      'Hume was born in 1711 in Scotland and became one of the leading figures of the Scottish Enlightenment. He wanted literary fame as well as philosophical insight, and his career included philosophical works, essays, history writing, diplomacy, and participation in learned sociability. The early Treatise of Human Nature was ambitious and initially disappointing in reception. Hume later recast parts of it in the Enquiries, which are more polished and accessible. The different versions matter because the Treatise is more architectonic and psychologically detailed, while the Enquiries often present the mature public face of his arguments.',
      'His setting was one of commercial society, religious controversy, scientific prestige, moral sense theory, and debate about politeness, history, and political economy. Hume did not write as an isolated destroyer of belief. He wrote as a participant in Enlightenment attempts to understand human nature empirically. He also held views on race and empire that are morally objectionable and should not be hidden behind admiration for his philosophical brilliance. Reading Hume responsibly means seeing both the power of his analysis and the historical limitations of his social imagination.'
    ],['empiricism','ethics','political-philosophy'],['hume','locke','kant'],['A Treatise of Human Nature','Essays Moral, Political, and Literary','The History of England']),
    section('copy-principle','Impressions, ideas, and the copy principle',[
      'Hume begins with perceptions, divided into impressions and ideas. Impressions are more forceful and lively: sensations, passions, emotions, and immediate experiences. Ideas are fainter copies used in thinking and reasoning. The copy principle says that every simple idea is derived from a corresponding simple impression. When a philosophical term becomes obscure, Hume asks from what impression the supposed idea is derived. If none can be found, suspicion is warranted.',
      'The principle is a tool of clarification, not a complete psychology by itself. Hume knows that imagination can compound, transpose, augment, and diminish ideas. We can imagine golden mountains because we combine ideas derived from experience. The famous missing shade of blue creates a complication: someone acquainted with many shades might form an idea of a missing shade without having experienced it. Hume treats this as too singular to overturn the general principle, but the case reveals that his empiricism is not mechanical recording. It is a disciplined test for whether philosophical concepts have experiential content.'
    ],['epistemology','empiricism','philosophy-of-mind'],['hume','locke'],['A Treatise of Human Nature','An Enquiry Concerning Human Understanding']),
    section('association-belief','Association, imagination, and belief',[
      'Hume explains much of mental life through principles of association: resemblance, contiguity in time or place, and cause or effect. These principles guide how one perception calls up another. Belief is not merely the addition of a logical tag to an idea. It is a more lively, forceful, steady way of conceiving an object, produced by habits of the imagination under regular conditions. This account makes belief psychologically intelligible without treating it as the conclusion of a formal proof.',
      'The role of imagination is double. It enables ordinary life by carrying the mind from present impressions to absent objects, future events, other persons, and enduring things. It also creates philosophical illusions when its habits are mistaken for rational insight into necessary connections or simple substances. Hume\'s method is therefore both descriptive and critical. He does not ask us to stop relying on imagination; that would be impossible. He asks us to understand which operations support stable practice and which produce metaphysical overreach.'
    ],['epistemology','philosophy-of-mind','empiricism'],['hume','locke','kant'],['A Treatise of Human Nature']),
    section('causation-induction','Causation, induction, and necessary connection',[
      'Hume\'s account of causation is the classic challenge. When we observe one event followed by another, we never perceive a necessary connection binding them. We perceive contiguity, priority, and constant conjunction. After repeated experience, the mind forms an expectation that the second kind of event will follow the first. The feeling of determination in the mind is then projected outward as necessary connection. Causal belief arises from custom, not from rational insight into powers.',
      'The problem of induction follows. No demonstrative argument proves that the future must resemble the past, because the contrary is conceivable without contradiction. No probable argument can justify induction without circularity, because it would already assume that past regularities are a guide to future regularities. Hume\'s point is not that we can stop making inductive inferences. Nature has made them unavoidable. The philosophical result is humbling: the foundation of empirical science and ordinary expectation is not reason alone but trained habit operating in a regular world.'
    ],['epistemology','empiricism','philosophy-of-science'],['hume','locke','kant'],['A Treatise of Human Nature','An Enquiry Concerning Human Understanding']),
    section('external-world-self','The external world and the bundle theory of the self',[
      'Hume applies similar pressure to belief in enduring external objects and a simple self. Experience gives us particular perceptions: colors, sounds, pains, pleasures, memories, desires, and thoughts. It does not present a bare substratum standing behind them. Belief in continued and distinct objects arises through the imagination\'s handling of constancy and coherence among perceptions. We naturally smooth interruptions and organize experience into enduring things. This belief is practically irresistible, but its philosophical justification is limited.',
      'The self receives even sharper treatment. When Hume looks inward, he finds no impression of a simple, identical self, only a bundle or collection of perceptions in flux. Memory and causal association create the fiction of identity by linking related perceptions. This does not mean that ordinary personal life vanishes. Hume continues to speak of persons, character, responsibility, and social relations. The point is that the metaphysical self as a simple substance cannot be found in experience. Later philosophers respond by asking whether Hume\'s own account of mental association presupposes some unity that he cannot explain.'
    ],['philosophy-of-mind','metaphysics','epistemology'],['hume','locke','descartes','kant'],['A Treatise of Human Nature']),
    section('reason-passions','Reason, passion, and motivation',[
      'Hume argues that reason alone does not move us to act. Reason discovers relations of ideas and matters of fact; it can inform us about means, consequences, and consistency. But motivation requires passion, desire, aversion, or sentiment. A person acts because something matters to them. The famous claim that reason is the slave of the passions is often misread as praise for irrationality. Hume\'s point is analytical: reason by itself supplies no final end. It serves, corrects, and redirects passions by showing facts and relations, but it does not generate desire from nothing.',
      'This account reshapes ethics. Moral philosophy cannot be built on pure rational perception of moral facts if such perception has no motivational force. At the same time, Hume does not reduce morality to selfish impulse. Sympathy, social feeling, concern for character, and shared practices make moral life possible. Practical reason matters enormously, but as part of a broader psychology of sentiment and convention. Hume\'s moral psychology remains influential because it refuses both cold rationalism and crude egoism.'
    ],['ethics','philosophy-of-mind','empiricism'],['hume','locke','kant'],['A Treatise of Human Nature','An Enquiry Concerning the Principles of Morals']),
    section('morality-sentiment','Morality, sympathy, and artificial virtues',[
      'Hume holds that moral distinctions are not derived from reason alone. We approve or disapprove of traits and actions through sentiment, especially when we consider them from a general point of view. Virtues are qualities useful or agreeable to oneself or others. Benevolence, generosity, prudence, justice, fidelity, and many other traits become intelligible through their effects on human flourishing and social life. Moral judgment is therefore rooted in human nature, but not merely in private taste, because sympathy and shared perspectives allow common standards to develop.',
      'Justice is especially important because Hume treats it as an artificial virtue. That does not mean fake or optional. It means that justice depends on conventions that arise under human conditions: limited generosity, scarcity, vulnerability, and the advantages of stable possession and promise-keeping. Rules of property and contract are human inventions, but they answer to real needs and become morally binding through their social utility. This differs from Locke\'s natural rights framework and from rationalist moral theories. It makes morality historical and conventional without reducing it to arbitrary command.'
    ],['ethics','political-philosophy','empiricism'],['hume','locke','kant'],['A Treatise of Human Nature','An Enquiry Concerning the Principles of Morals']),
    section('religion-miracles-design','Religion, miracles, and natural theology',[
      'Hume\'s philosophy of religion is cautious, sharp, and often devastating to traditional apologetics. In the Enquiry, the essay on miracles argues that testimony for a miracle must be weighed against the uniform experience supporting the laws of nature. Since a miracle is a violation of that regularity, the evidence for the testimony must be stronger than the evidence against the event. Hume also considers human tendencies toward wonder, religious enthusiasm, and unreliable transmission. The argument does not require proving that miracles are impossible; it challenges whether testimony can rationally establish them.',
      'The Dialogues Concerning Natural Religion examines arguments from design. Cleanthes argues from the order of the world to an intelligent designer; Philo raises skeptical objections about analogy, evil, anthropomorphism, and the limits of inference from a single universe; Demea represents a more mystical or a priori tendency. The dialogue form prevents easy reduction to one speech, but Hume clearly pressures confident natural theology. His Natural History of Religion explains religious belief through fear, hope, ignorance, and anthropomorphic imagination. Together these works make religion a human phenomenon to be studied, not only a doctrine to be proven or refuted.'
    ],['philosophy-of-religion','epistemology','empiricism'],['hume','spinoza','kant'],['An Enquiry Concerning Human Understanding','Dialogues Concerning Natural Religion','The Natural History of Religion']),
    section('politics-history-commerce','Politics, history, and commercial society',[
      'Hume\'s political thought is less famous than Locke\'s but deeply important. He is suspicious of social contract theories that treat political obligation as if it rested on an original promise most people never made. Governments arise through history, force, habit, utility, and the need for order. Allegiance becomes justified when institutions serve common interests, secure peace, and support the conditions of social life. This does not make Hume an enemy of liberty; it makes him wary of grounding politics in fictions about consent.',
      'His essays on commerce, parties, refinement, and constitutional balance helped shape modern political economy and historical sociology. He saw commercial society as capable of softening manners and increasing prosperity, though not without risks of inequality, dependence, and corruption. As a historian, he interpreted institutions through gradual development rather than simple founding moments. His politics reflects the same naturalism as his epistemology: look at how human beings actually form expectations, loyalties, conventions, and institutions, then ask which arrangements work tolerably well for creatures like us.'
    ],['political-philosophy','empiricism','ethics'],['hume','locke'],['Essays Moral, Political, and Literary','The History of England']),
    section('aesthetics-taste','Taste, art, and standards of judgment',[
      'Hume\'s essay on the standard of taste addresses a problem parallel to ethics. Judgments of beauty seem rooted in sentiment, yet we also argue about better and worse taste. Hume does not try to turn beauty into a property perceived by pure reason. Instead he asks what conditions make a critic reliable: delicacy of imagination, practice, comparison, freedom from prejudice, and good sense. Standards arise from the convergent judgments of qualified critics under favorable conditions.',
      'This approach shows Hume\'s broader strategy. He accepts that judgment depends on human sentiment, then asks how sentiment can be educated, corrected, and made shareable. Aesthetic disagreement is not solved by declaring every reaction equal or by pretending sentiment is irrelevant. It requires attention to experience, cultivation, context, and the removal of distorting bias. The same structure appears in moral judgment: human feelings are the basis, but not every immediate feeling deserves equal authority.'
    ],['aesthetics','ethics','empiricism'],['hume'],['Of the Standard of Taste','Essays Moral, Political, and Literary']),
    section('influence-misunderstandings','Influence, misunderstandings, and interpretive tensions',[
      'Hume\'s influence is vast. Kant famously credits Hume with disrupting dogmatic metaphysics, especially through the problem of causation. Logical positivists, analytic philosophers, naturalists, moral sentimentalists, skeptics, political theorists, and philosophers of religion all return to Hume. He helped make it impossible to discuss induction, causation, miracles, personal identity, and moral motivation without facing the limits he exposed. He also influenced economics and historical explanation through his essays and histories.',
      'Misunderstandings are just as common. Hume is not a global skeptic who thinks ordinary life should stop. He is not saying science is worthless because induction lacks rational proof. He is not claiming morality is mere arbitrary feeling. He is not simply an atheist pamphleteer, though his religious skepticism is profound. The interpretive tensions are real: whether Hume\'s naturalism answers or merely lives with skepticism; whether his account of the self can explain unity of consciousness; whether moral sentiment can support criticism of corrupt sentiments; whether his politics is too conservative about existing authority; and how his prejudiced remarks about race should affect our assessment of his Enlightenment universalism.'
    ],['empiricism','epistemology','ethics','philosophy-of-religion'],['hume','locke','kant'],['A Treatise of Human Nature','An Enquiry Concerning Human Understanding','Dialogues Concerning Natural Religion']),
    section('reading-strategy','A reading strategy for Hume',[
      'Begin with the Enquiry Concerning Human Understanding for a polished path into impressions, ideas, causation, induction, liberty, miracles, and skeptical limits. Then read the corresponding sections of the Treatise, especially Book I on understanding and Book II on passions, to see the deeper psychological machinery. The Enquiry Concerning the Principles of Morals is often the best route into Hume\'s ethics because it presents sympathy, utility, and virtue with clarity. Pair those readings with selected essays on taste, politics, and commerce to avoid reducing Hume to a single skeptical argument.',
      'Read Hume by asking what operation of the mind he is explaining. Is this belief produced by demonstration, experience, custom, sentiment, sympathy, convention, or education? Also ask what survives the skeptical argument in ordinary life. Hume often exposes the lack of rational foundation and then shows that human nature carries us on anyway. That double movement is the key. He is neither simply destroying reason nor restoring old certainties. He is teaching philosophy to become honest about the natural conditions under which belief, morality, science, religion, and politics actually operate.'
    ],['empiricism','epistemology','ethics','political-philosophy'],['hume','locke','kant'],['An Enquiry Concerning Human Understanding','A Treatise of Human Nature','An Enquiry Concerning the Principles of Morals','Essays Moral, Political, and Literary'])
  ]
};
